= Export Maya geoCache =

"""Exports Houdini point geometry as a Maya geometry cache (.xml + .mc files)."""

== Overview ==

This node bakes a Houdini geometry sequence into the Maya geometry cache
format (one `.mc` file per frame plus an `.xml` descriptor). The resulting
files can be loaded in Maya via __Cache > Geometry Cache > Attach Existing
Cache__.

Each unique value of the prim string attribute (set in __Name Attribute__)
becomes one channel in the cache.  Maya maps each channel to a mesh by
matching the channel name against the mesh's **shape node name**.

== The `name` Attribute and Maya Shape Nodes ==

The prim attribute value must match the Maya **shape node name** — not the
transform node name.

:tip:
    In Maya's Outliner, enable __Show > Shapes__ to see shape nodes.  Shape
    node names typically end in `Shape` (e.g. the transform `pSphere1` has a
    shape node named `pSphereShape1`).  Use that shape node name as the prim
    attribute value in Houdini.

:warning:
    Maya drives deformation by replacing vertex positions in index order.
    The point count and point order for each name value must be identical to
    the target Maya mesh and must not change between frames.

== Parameters ==

Start Frame:
    First frame to cache.

End Frame:
    Last frame to cache (inclusive).

Evaluation Rate:
    Fraction of a frame between successive cache samples.  `1` = one sample
    per frame.  `0.5` = two samples per frame (sub-frame caching).

XML:
    Full path to the output `.xml` descriptor file.  Per-frame `.mc` files
    are written to the same directory as `<base>Frame<N>.mc`.

Name Attribute:
    Name of the prim string attribute used to identify which Maya shape node
    each primitive belongs to.  Defaults to `name`.  Primitives with an
    empty value are skipped.

Cache:
    Click to start the export.  A progress dialog allows cancellation.

Python Module Path:
    Path to `nCache.py`.  The HDA loads the module from this path each time
    __Cache__ is pressed.

== How to Attach the Cache in Maya ==

# Select one or more mesh objects in Maya.
# Go to __Cache > Geometry Cache > Attach Existing Cache__.
# Select the `.xml` file exported by this HDA.
# Maya matches each channel to a selected shape by name and wires up the
  connections automatically.  Shapes with no matching channel are skipped.

:note:
    Do not use __File > Import__ — it will not set up the cache connections.
